{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01PRCZGAHZNA6C5q3bZfhoNK","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now all 3 pods are showing `0/1` (not Ready). This is more concerning. The StatefulSet is 19m old but the cluster was just recently started (pods at 2-13 minutes old).\n\nThis appears to be an issue where the readiness probes are failing for all nodes now. The `cockroach node status` showed all nodes as live/available, but the HTTP readiness endpoint is returning 503.\n\nWait - in CockroachDB, the readiness probe checks `https://:http/health?ready=1`. The 503 status means the node is not ready to serve SQL traffic. This can happen if:\n- The node is still initializing\n- The cluster hasn't been initialized yet (needs `cockroach init`)\n- There's a certificate issue with the HTTPS endpoint\n\nThe node status showed all nodes as available and live, including node 2, so the issue might be specific to how the HTTPS readiness probe is being verified. The kubelet might not be configured to use the client certificates properly, causing the probe to fail even though the nodes are actually healthy. The `/health?ready=1` endpoint returns 200 when ready and 503 when not, so I need to figure out why it's returning 503 despite the nodes being live.\n\nLooking at this from the upgrade perspective: the StatefulSet already has v24.1.0 as the image and the pods were restarted with it, but the readiness probes are failing. This could mean either a rolling update partition was set to prevent the rollout and then removed, causing the pods to cycle through with issues, or there's something else blocking the upgrade process.\n\nThe real question is whether the image was already v24.1.0 before I started or if it needed to be changed. Since the task is to upgrade to v24.1.0 and the pods are currently failing health checks, I should investigate whether the `cockroach-certs` secret is properly configured for the HTTPS readiness probe, as that could be preventing the pods from becoming ready even though they're running the right version. Looking at the pod logs, I notice crdb-cluster-2 took 426 seconds to start up, which is extremely slow, and it still couldn't properly contact the other nodes in the cluster even after that long initialization period. This startup delay combined with the inter-node communication issues suggests the cluster is having fundamental connectivity or resource problems.\n\nThe readiness probe configuration requires 2 consecutive failures to mark the pod as not ready, and crdb-cluster-2 accumulated 89 failures over 13 minutes, indicating persistent health check issues even after the nodes eventually connected to each other.\n\nThis is puzzling because a rolling update should have been blocked if crdb-cluster-2 was already failing its readiness probe—the StatefulSet wouldn't proceed to restart crdb-cluster-0 until the previous pod was Ready. Yet all three pods are now running v24.1.0 with partition=0, suggesting the update completed despite the readiness failures.\n\nThe real disconnect is between the node status showing all nodes as live and available in the cluster, yet the readiness probes consistently returning 503 errors. That mismatch is what I need to understand.\n\nLet me check if I can actually establish a SQL connection using the certificates to see if the nodes are truly unable to serve requests or if it's just an HTTP endpoint issue.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":728,"cache_read_input_tokens":36131,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":728},"output_tokens":27,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9890bff2-62c4-4c97-b1f2-1767ee9bac2a","uuid":"c300db82-923e-4992-bddf-57db9e2feba6","request_id":"req_011CcMbSFiULcEFxmYoDvbJk"}
