{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01WbVuuV5bsCLJaSkcrD4myo","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The rollout is showing \"partitioned roll out complete: 3 new pods have been updated...\" - which means Kubernetes considers the rolling update complete. All 3 pods have been updated.\n\nBut all pods are 0/1. The `kubectl rollout status` reports the rollout as complete because all pods have been updated to the new version, but the pods' readiness state is separate from the rollout completion status.\n\nLet me now focus on why the readiness probes are failing. The cert exists (I can see the PEM header). Let me try to actually check the SANs using a different method.\nI'm noticing something odd about the readiness probe failures. The warning shows x89 failures over 12 minutes, which works out to roughly one failure every 8 seconds. Since the probe runs every 5 seconds, that means almost every single probe is failing. Yet when I check from inside the pod, `/health?ready=1` returns 200. There's a disconnect here between what the kubelet is seeing and what I'm observing directly.\n\nActually, I'm second-guessing the curl command I ran. The `?` character in the URL might not have been passed correctly through the kubectl exec shell due to quoting issues. Let me reconsider how the shell interprets that query parameter.\n\nThe `?` is actually a glob character in bash that matches any single character, so `health?ready=1` could match files like `health_ready=1` in the container's working directory. If no files match that pattern, bash might handle it differently depending on the shell settings. Looking back at the response I got—an empty JSON object with HTTP 200—that looks like the response from just `/health` without the query parameter, which always returns 200 if the server is running. The `/health?ready=1` endpoint should return 503 if the node isn't ready, so the `?` might have been stripped or interpreted as a glob that didn't match anything.\n\nI should retest this with proper URL quoting to ensure the query parameter gets passed correctly to CockroachDB.\n\nActually, the real issue might be TLS certificate verification in the kubelet probes.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":758,"cache_read_input_tokens":43830,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":758},"output_tokens":34,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9890bff2-62c4-4c97-b1f2-1767ee9bac2a","uuid":"6f1f6436-edc4-4a90-8f96-826a6f0a36e5","request_id":"req_011CcMbbTvwNUjLvNQmDL2td"}
