{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01EGmeE7q8ccrg3mWgnTcL63","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, so:\n1. From inside the pod, `https://localhost:8080/health?ready=1` returns 200 with proper quoting\n2. Kubernetes 1.31.0 is running\n\nIn Kubernetes 1.23+, HTTPS probes DO verify TLS certificates by default. The cert needs to have the correct SANs that include the pod IP or `localhost`.\n\nNow, the pod cert at `/cockroach/cockroach-certs/node.crt` - let me check its SANs. Let me use a Python-based approach since the container doesn't have openssl.\n\nActually wait, the container might have openssl. Let me check.\nThe issue is likely that the kubelet is connecting to the pod's actual IP address (like 10.244.x.x) on port 8080 via HTTPS, but the node certificate only has the service DNS name in its SAN list, not the pod IP or localhost. When TLS verification fails on an HTTPS probe in Kubernetes, it typically returns an HTTP error.\n\nLooking at the actual error message though—\"HTTP probe failed with statuscode: 503\"—this suggests TLS handshake succeeded and CockroachDB is legitimately returning a 503 status. So the real question is whether the `/health?ready=1` endpoint is actually returning 503 because the node isn't ready, or if there's something else going on with how the probe is being executed.\n\nLet me check the StatefulSet configuration to see if there's an `InsecureSkipTLSVerify` flag or other probe settings that might explain the discrepancy between what I'm seeing inside the pod versus what the kubelet is observing.\n\nLooking at the readiness probe configuration, there's no `insecureSkipTLSVerify` field present. In Kubernetes 1.31, HTTPS probes verify TLS certificates by default, and there's actually no way to disable this verification at the probe level anymore—the kubelet always validates the certificate for HTTPS probes. This means the certificate's Subject Alternative Names need to match what the kubelet is connecting to, whether that's the pod IP, hostname, or localhost.\n\nBut if this was already an issue before the upgrade, something must have changed during the upgrade itself. Either the certificate was regenerated with different SANs, or there's something about how this scenario was set up that's causing the probes to fail. Let me check if there's a StatefulSet revision history or a deployment manifest that shows what changed, or if this is intentionally part of the scenario design where the student needs to fix the readiness probes.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1333,"cache_read_input_tokens":44588,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1333},"output_tokens":39,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9890bff2-62c4-4c97-b1f2-1767ee9bac2a","uuid":"d231659d-331e-48bb-8ef6-08be4311d729","request_id":"req_011CcMbdBN6LvSKwWcWZ9CXu"}
