{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01MG2kqGBikMinWy1mr8aRZH","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The logs show that crdb-cluster-0 started successfully (37.4s startup time) as \"restarted pre-existing node\" with nodeID=1. The image was already present (no pull needed). \n\nThe events don't show any recent Unhealthy events for crdb-cluster-0 (the event list only goes back to the pod creation). Wait, the earlier describe showed x89 failures for crdb-cluster-2 over 12 minutes. For crdb-cluster-0, there might be failures too, but they're not shown in the truncated events list.\n\nActually, looking at the pod age: crdb-cluster-0 is now 6m59s old. \n\nWith the readiness probe checking every 5 seconds after a 10-second initial delay, that's roughly 82 probe attempts since the restart. The absence of \"Unhealthy\" events in the describe output suggests it might not be failing the probe currently, though the events could be truncated. But here's the critical detail: the initial pod listing showed crdb-cluster-0 as 1/1 ready at 62 seconds, yet now at nearly 7 minutes it's showing 0/1 — meaning it was ready and then became unready.\n\nThis is puzzling because it suggests the pod recovered initially but then failed again. Looking at the StatefulSet rolling update mechanics, the controller updates pods from highest to lowest ordinal, and each pod must be Ready before the next one updates. If crdb-cluster-2 was stuck at 0/1 while crdb-cluster-1 was being updated, that shouldn't have been possible under standard rolling update constraints with a partition setting.\n\nThe most likely explanation is that crdb-cluster-2 briefly passed its readiness probes after restarting, allowing the rolling update to proceed through the other pods, but then started failing readiness checks again. The fact that it's now showing 1/1 at 17 minutes suggests it eventually recovered, while the other pods have maintained their Ready status throughout.\n\nBut crdb-cluster-0 is the real anomaly here—it was Ready at 62 seconds but dropped to not Ready around 3 minutes and has stayed that way for several minutes. Given that the test path contains \"adversary\" in it, I'm wondering if there's some kind of failure injection or adversarial condition being introduced that's specifically affecting crdb-cluster-0.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2930,"cache_read_input_tokens":49980,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2930},"output_tokens":29,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9890bff2-62c4-4c97-b1f2-1767ee9bac2a","uuid":"3e172969-33f4-42f7-95c8-f61c7d524e6b","request_id":"req_011CcMbkPgCbqMchbu6JR5Xc"}
