{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_014cW18oNWZFAKekfknHASZj","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This is VERY revealing. Looking at the events:\n\n1. 18m ago: crdb-cluster-2 was killed and recreated\n2. 16m ago: BOTH crdb-cluster-0 and crdb-cluster-1 were KILLED simultaneously!\n3. Then both were recreated (14m ago)\n4. At 9m42s ago: crdb-cluster-0 had readiness probe failure (503)\n5. At 9m25s ago: crdb-cluster-0 was KILLED AGAIN (Pulled/Created/Started events at 9m25s/24s/22s)\n6. At 8m40s ago: crdb-cluster-0 was killed yet again\n7. At 7m35s ago: crdb-cluster-0 was created (current version)\n\nThe pattern is unmistakable—crdb-cluster-0 keeps restarting in a cycle, with each instance surviving only a few minutes before being killed. It's been failing readiness checks constantly since the 7m35s restart, roughly every 16 seconds, which suggests the pod is stuck in a crash loop.\n\nLooking at the timeline more carefully: the pod started 14 minutes ago, hit a readiness failure at 9m42s, got killed and recreated at 9m25s, then killed again at 8m40s after only 44 seconds, and now the current instance has been running since 7m35s. The `Killing` event type typically indicates the StatefulSet controller is performing a rolling update, but I need to check what the partition setting is on the StatefulSet to understand why it's doing this. So the controller would only restart crdb-cluster-0 again if there's another update being applied. Given the path mentions an adversary benchmark, this could be an adversary injection causing repeated rolling updates—maybe resetting the partition or toggling the image back and forth. Let me look more carefully at the event timeline to understand what's triggering these repeated kills.\n\nActually, both crdb-cluster-0 and crdb-cluster-1 were killed at exactly the same time 16 minutes ago, which isn't how StatefulSet rolling updates work—they kill pods sequentially. Combined with crdb-cluster-2 being killed 18 minutes ago, all three pods went down in a short window, suggesting either an adversary disruption, a kubectl delete command, or some external event. After the restart, the cluster has been struggling to reach Ready state, and crdb-cluster-0 is now failing readiness probes with 503 errors.\n\nLooking at the sequence more closely, crdb-cluster-0 failed its readiness check at 9m42s, then a new instance was pulled and started around 9m25s, killed again at 8m40s, and yet another one was created at 7m35s. This rapid cycling suggests something is repeatedly killing the pod—likely the StatefulSet controller during a rolling update, but I need to check what the partition setting is to understand why it's being so aggressive.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2148,"cache_read_input_tokens":54647,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2148},"output_tokens":27,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9890bff2-62c4-4c97-b1f2-1767ee9bac2a","uuid":"5215d6aa-118a-4bc8-8f1e-111495a96f10","request_id":"req_011CcMbo7BM8P6NspdFR4WTg"}
