{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01VT578vzGXs298oF9eNdduA","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This is VERY revealing! The last-applied-configuration annotation shows the StatefulSet was applied with:\n\n1. `--insecure` flag (not `--certs-dir`)\n2. `COCKROACH_CHANNEL: kubernetes-insecure`\n3. HTTP probes (NOT HTTPS): `httpGet.path: /health` and no `scheme: HTTPS`\n4. NO volumes for certs\n5. `volumeMounts` only has `datadir` (no certs mount)\n\nBut the CURRENT StatefulSet spec has:\n- HTTPS probes\n- Certs directory\n- Certs volume\n\nSo there's a mismatch between what was originally applied (insecure mode) and what's actually running now (secure mode with certificates). The StatefulSet has been modified from its intended insecure configuration to use TLS, which is why the args show `--certs-dir=/cockroach/cockroach-certs` instead of the `--insecure` flag that was in the desired state.\n\nThe readiness probes also differ—the original config used HTTP without HTTPS, but the running pods are now using HTTPS probes. This explains why crdb-cluster-0 is failing its readiness check while the other pods that have been running longer seem to be passing theirs. The question is whether the secure configuration is actually the intended state or if we need to revert back to insecure mode.\n\nLooking at the last-applied-configuration, it already shows the v24.1.0 image, which means the upgrade was already applied via kubectl apply and the rolling update is currently in progress. But the current StatefulSet spec has HTTPS probes and certificates enabled, which suggests something or someone has modified the configuration beyond what was originally applied.\n\nThis mismatch is causing the readiness probe failures—the insecure mode pods don't have certificates, so when the probes try to connect via HTTPS, they fail. Yet crdb-cluster-1 and crdb-cluster-2 are passing their probes despite running the same configuration, which is puzzling. Let me look more closely at the actual pod specs and the specific probe errors to understand what's happening. a rolling update that progressed through the pods. Now crdb-cluster-2 and crdb-cluster-1 have recovered and are Ready, but crdb-cluster-0 is still failing—which is strange since it's the newest. I need to figure out why the readiness probes are passing for the older pods but not the latest one, especially since there's a mismatch between the HTTPS probes and the `--insecure` flag the pods are actually running with.\n\nLooking at the actual current pod specs rather than the last-applied configuration, I can see that crdb-cluster-2 is running with TLS certificates and HTTPS health checks configured, which explains why it eventually became Ready despite the annotation showing an insecure configuration. The pods must have been patched or updated after the initial apply. Actually, I need to look more carefully at crdb-cluster-0 specifically. Looking at the event timeline, I can see a pattern: all three pods were killed 18 minutes ago, then crdb-cluster-0 and crdb-cluster-1 were killed again around 16 minutes ago during what looks like a rolling update. Since then, crdb-cluster-0 has been repeatedly killed and recreated multiple times over the last 7-9 minutes, suggesting it's stuck in a crash loop while the other two pods stabilized. killed and recreated multiple times, either something's deleting the pod externally or the liveness probe is failing. But liveness probe failures normally just restart the container within the same pod, not create a new one—though I'm second-guessing whether StatefulSets handle this differently. The kubelet's killing events suggest it could be a liveness failure, but that shouldn't trigger a full pod recreation by the StatefulSet controller.\n\nWait, the `Killing` event followed by `SuccessfulCreate` means the old pod was actually deleted and a new one created, which only happens if the StatefulSet controller is doing a rolling update. So it's not just a liveness probe issue—the controller is actively terminating and recreating the pod. The `podManagementPolicy: Parallel` setting allows concurrent pod operations, but with a RollingUpdate strategy, updates should still happen sequentially, so something's triggering repeated updates.\n\nThe multiple restarts of crdb-cluster-0 might be intentional—possibly the adversary is deliberately causing the pod to be recreated repeatedly.\n\nLet me check what the current pod spec is actually running to see if it's using the secure or insecure configuration. From the events and current state, I can see crdb-cluster-0 is on v24.1.0 and failing readiness probes, but when I tested the health endpoint directly from inside the pod with HTTPS, it returned 200.\n\nLooking at the probe events more carefully, there's a critical difference: the older warning from 14 minutes ago shows the probe was using HTTP and got \"connection refused\", but the current warning shows it's now getting HTTP 503. This suggests the pod configuration changed—it's no longer refusing the connection, but the endpoint is returning an error status.\n\nThe StatefulSet must have been patched to switch from HTTP to HTTPS probes, which explains why the old pod was using plain HTTP and the new one is using HTTPS. Now I need to figure out whether the 503 is coming from a TLS certificate mismatch (kubelet can't verify the cert for the pod IP) or if CockroachDB is legitimately returning that status code.\n\nSince crdb-cluster-1 and crdb-cluster-2 eventually became Ready with the same HTTPS probes, it seems unlikely that the 503 is a legitimate CockroachDB response—unless crdb-cluster-0 is still syncing data from the restart, though seven minutes should be more than enough time for that to complete. Let me trace through the timeline more carefully to understand what actually happened. So crdb-cluster-0 was pulled at 9m25s, killed at 8m40s (about 45 seconds of runtime), then the StatefulSet controller created a replacement at 7m35s with the container pulling again at 7m29s. This pod is cycling through rapid restart cycles.\n\nThe pattern is suspicious—crdb-cluster-0 keeps getting terminated while the other two pods remain stable, and even though the rolling update should be complete (updateRevision matches currentRevision), the pod continues to be killed repeatedly. Something is actively targeting just this pod.\n\nNow I need to focus on the actual problem: crdb-cluster-0 is returning 200 when I test the endpoint directly from inside the pod, but the kubelet sees a 503 from the readiness probe. The most likely explanation is a configuration mismatch—let me pull the pod specs for all three and compare them side by side.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2661,"cache_read_input_tokens":56795,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2661},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9890bff2-62c4-4c97-b1f2-1767ee9bac2a","uuid":"98f7c173-c765-4a1e-ad02-3398ff78800b","request_id":"req_011CcMbqSBQhDKdGn9VV3KRA"}
