{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015SMdFxBnNKT9QRvHBfhc5S","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The pod specs are IDENTICAL. Both pods have:\n- Same args (using `--certs-dir`)\n- Same readiness probe (HTTPS)\n\nSo the config is the same for both. Yet crdb-cluster-1 is Ready (1/1) and crdb-cluster-0 is Not Ready (0/1).\n\nThis eliminates configuration differences as the cause.\n\nLet me look at what's different. crdb-cluster-0 has been failing since ~7 minutes (currently running instance started 7m35s ago). The HTTPS probe connects to the pod IP via port 8080 and gets 503.\nWhen I curl the endpoint from inside the pod, `/health?ready=1` returns 200. The kubelet's probe differs in two ways: it connects to the pod IP rather than localhost, and it verifies the TLS certificate instead of skipping verification. I should test the endpoint with proper TLS verification from inside the pod to match the kubelet's behavior, and also check what SANs are configured on the node certificate—if it only has the hostname and not the pod IP, that could be causing the TLS verification to fail.\n\nBut here's the puzzle: crdb-cluster-1 also uses HTTPS probes and the kubelet connects to its pod IP too, yet it's not failing. This suggests either the certificate includes all pod IPs as SANs, or something else is allowing the verification to pass. Since all pods share the same secret `cockroachdb-certs`, I need to figure out whether that single certificate covers all pod IPs or if there's something else going on with how the kubelet handles the verification.\n\nActually, I'm realizing that CockroachDB typically generates node certificates with wildcard hostname patterns like `*.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local`, which wouldn't include the actual pod IPs. If TLS verification was failing, Kubernetes would report it differently than a 503 status code—TLS errors show up as connection failures, not HTTP status codes. The fact that I'm seeing a 503 means the HTTPS connection actually succeeded, which means the TLS verification passed somehow.\n\nSo the real puzzle is why CockroachDB returns 503 to the kubelet probe but 200 when I curl from inside the pod. The difference is that my curl connects to localhost (127.0.0.1) while the kubelet connects to the pod IP. I'm wondering if CockroachDB has different behavior based on the source IP—maybe it treats localhost connections differently than external ones.\n\nActually, I just realized something important: my curl test used `-k` to skip TLS verification, so it was connecting insecurely. The kubelet, on the other hand, verifies the certificate. If the cert only includes the pod hostname in its SAN and not localhost or the pod IP, then TLS verification would fail for both cases, but the behavior might differ depending on how CockroachDB handles cert mismatches.\n\nBut here's the thing: if TLS fails, Kubernetes would report a TLS error, not a 503 status code. Since we're seeing 503, that means TLS is succeeding and the server is actually returning that status. So the cert must have the pod IP as a SAN.\n\nThat brings me back to the real question: why would CockroachDB return 503 to the kubelet probe but 200 from localhost? One possibility is that the `/health?ready=1` endpoint checks cluster readiness, and crdb-cluster-0 might still be catching up on replicated data even though it can serve basic requests locally. The other nodes have been running longer, so they've had more time to sync.\n\nLooking at the node status, crdb-cluster-0 shows `is_available: true`, which in CockroachDB means the node has been up for at least 5 minutes and hasn't failed liveness checks.\n\nBut that's different from the HTTP readiness probe failing. The contradiction here is interesting—the node appears healthy by CockroachDB's internal metrics but the readiness endpoint is returning 503. I should test the readiness endpoint without the `-k` flag to see if TLS verification is actually the culprit, since skipping client-side verification with `-k` might have masked the real issue.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5245,"cache_read_input_tokens":59456,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":5245},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9890bff2-62c4-4c97-b1f2-1767ee9bac2a","uuid":"9497015f-35e4-4c21-b999-0efe56186157","request_id":"req_011CcMbwdbRMG3QWH3BkevaG"}
