{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_0169By9sFpWeP5522jwtfyPQ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The TLS cert does NOT include the pod IP address (10.244.0.143) as a Subject Alternative Name (SAN). The cert only has hostnames (like `crdb-cluster-0.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local`), not the IP.\n\nThis is the root cause of the readiness probe failure! The kubelet connects to the pod IP via HTTPS, and the TLS cert doesn't include the pod IP as a SAN. TLS verification fails.\n\nBut wait - why are crdb-cluster-1 and crdb-cluster-2 passing their readiness probes? They should have the SAME cert issue (same `cockroachdb-certs` secret, same cert without pod IPs).\nI'm wondering if the kubelet's TLS verification behavior differs across Kubernetes versions or if there's a feature gate involved, but that doesn't explain why the other pods are passing their probes when they should hit the same cert mismatch error. Ah, that's the key insight—the kubelet doesn't verify TLS certificates for HTTPS probes by default in Kubernetes. So when the probe connects to the pod IP, TLS succeeds without cert validation, and it receives the 503 HTTP response. This means the TLS certificate mismatch isn't actually causing the probe failure—it's the 503 status code itself that's the problem.\n\nNow I'm wondering if there's a difference in how the request is being made. The kubelet connects to the pod IP directly, and CockroachDB binds to `0.0.0.0:8080`, so it should respond the same way regardless of the source. But maybe the kubelet isn't sending the proper TLS SNI (Server Name Indication) in the ClientHello, which could affect how CockroachDB handles the request or which certificate it presents.\n\nActually, TLS is completing successfully since the kubelet gets past the handshake and receives a 503 response, so the certificate must be valid. The real question is why CockroachDB is returning 503 specifically. 