{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Ue7kFqwRHHrLeJbdVauRHY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"CRITICAL FINDING! From crdb-cluster-1's node status:\n\n- Node 1 (crdb-cluster-0): `is_available: true`, `is_live: true` ← only node 0 is live/available\n- Node 2 (crdb-cluster-2): `is_available: false`, `is_live: false` ← DEAD!\n- Node 3 (crdb-cluster-1): `is_available: false`, `is_live: false` ← DEAD! (the node that's running the command!)\n\nWait, this is really confusing. From crdb-cluster-1:\n- It's reporting itself as unavailable and dead\n- Node 2 is also marked as dead\n- Yet both crdb-cluster-1 and crdb-cluster-2 show as Ready in Kubernetes\n\nThe logs reveal the real problem: liveness heartbeats are failing across all nodes, including node 1 itself, with errors about failed epoch increments. This is a critical cluster health issue that could cascade into complete cluster failure.\n\nThe liveness heartbeat mechanism depends on a special system range having quorum. After the rolling updates and adversary disruptions caused multiple restarts, some ranges became unavailable—including potentially the liveness range itself. I'm seeing the heartbeat failure metrics spike dramatically on node 0 (peaking at 23 failures around 06:19:21), then drop to 1-3, and now node 1 is experiencing massive heartbeat failures at 06:24:11. The cluster is in severe distress.\n\nThe Kubernetes status shows only crdb-cluster-0 as Ready (1/1), while the other two nodes appear down (0/1). With just one live node out of three, the cluster loses quorum and can't make progress on any ranges. But there's a contradiction—when I checked the node status from crdb-cluster-0 earlier, it reported all three nodes as alive and available, which doesn't match the current Kubernetes readiness state.\n\nNow looking at the node status from crdb-cluster-1, it shows a completely different view: crdb-cluster-0 is alive, but both crdb-cluster-2 and crdb-cluster-1 are marked unavailable and not live. This divergence between what different nodes see suggests a clock skew or liveness epoch conflict. The \"heartbeat failed on epoch increment\" error is pointing to exactly this—when a node is declared dead by the cluster, the cluster increments that node's liveness epoch to expire its leases, but then when the node comes back online, there's a conflict between its view and the cluster's view of its epoch.\n\nThis pattern typically emerges during rolling restarts or upgrades when nodes restart too quickly, the liveness heartbeat interval is too aggressive, or storage I/O is slow enough to trigger liveness timeouts. The slow raft commit times I'm seeing (836ms) confirm there's I/O latency contributing to the liveness failures.\n\nSo the cluster is degraded, but stepping back—the actual upgrade task is technically complete since all pods are running v24.1.0. The readiness probe is failing on crdb-cluster-0 because the cluster itself has health issues with unavailable ranges, not because the image upgrade failed.\n\nLooking at the node status timestamps more carefully, the updates are very recent (within the last minute), which suggests the cluster might be in the process of self-healing as nodes catch up. The \"heartbeat failed on epoch increment\" errors appear to be transient conflicts that could resolve on their own. Let me wait a moment and check the status again to see if things are stabilizing. ) but the node's own liveness check doesn't immediately affect the HTTP readiness endpoint. If a node fails its liveness heartbeat, it should mark itself as not ready and return 503, which explains why crdb-cluster-0 is showing that error. But crdb-cluster-1 and crdb-cluster-2 might have just started failing their liveness checks too, and the Kubernetes readiness probe hasn't caught up with those recent failures yet.\n\nThe real problem seems to be that the entire cluster is struggling with liveness heartbeats due to slow I/O on this test cluster, causing pods to cycle in and out of readiness. I could wait for things to stabilize, dig into what's causing the slow I/O, or check if there's an adversary process running that's disrupting the cluster. Let me look for any adversary processes first.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2245,"cache_read_input_tokens":71906,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2245},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9890bff2-62c4-4c97-b1f2-1767ee9bac2a","uuid":"f320dfe2-1acb-4673-b130-e9ae325189e5","request_id":"req_011CcMc6wN1HY9NxJMQG3sxB"}
