{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_018mYG17aXYwTBWVCFczcLjE","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now the state has changed again:\n- crdb-cluster-0: 1/1 (Ready!) - 12m old\n- crdb-cluster-1: 1/1 (Ready) - 19m old\n- crdb-cluster-2: 0/1 (NOT Ready) - 23m old\n\nThe StatefulSet is 2/3 Ready again.\n\nAnd from `node status` run from crdb-cluster-0:\n- Node 1 (crdb-cluster-0): is_available: false, is_live: false\n- Node 2 (crdb-cluster-2): is_available: false, is_live: false\n- Node 3 (crdb-cluster-1): is_available: true, is_live: true\n\nSo nodes 1 and 2 are both down, but node 3 is actually healthy and available.\n\nNow comparing this against what Kubernetes reports: crdb-cluster-0 and crdb-cluster-1 both show as Ready, while crdb-cluster-2 is NotReady. The node status from crdb-cluster-0's perspective aligns with this—crdb-cluster-2 is unavailable, but there's something odd about crdb-cluster-0 itself reporting as unavailable when Kubernetes says it's Ready. Node 3 is the only one showing as both available and live, yet the query that revealed this was executed from node 1, which reports itself as dead. This points to a liveness epoch mismatch—the node can still execute SQL queries and serve traffic, but its liveness record in the cluster metadata says otherwise.\n\nThe real problem is that nodes 1 and 2 can't heartbeat their liveness records, which means they can't hold Raft leadership or serve as lease holders for ranges that depend on them. The cluster appears to have quorum on the surface, but the liveness mechanism is fundamentally broken. Looking at the logs, the `heartbeat failed on epoch increment` error suggests these nodes were already marked dead by the cluster, their epochs were incremented to expire their leases, and now they're stuck trying to reclaim their liveness status but failing in the process.\n\nThe pods keep cycling through different states—sometimes node 0 is down, sometimes node 2 is down—which is making the situation worse. The cluster should eventually self-heal through retries, but the constant pod restarts are preventing that recovery from happening.\n\nI'm wondering if there's an adversary deliberately causing these liveness disruptions. The task path mentions \"adversary,\" so I should check if there's a process actively interfering with the cluster's heartbeat mechanism or if there's adversary configuration I'm missing.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3151,"cache_read_input_tokens":74151,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3151},"output_tokens":30,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9890bff2-62c4-4c97-b1f2-1767ee9bac2a","uuid":"3335df2f-54b6-48d4-9b79-d554c52bfaee","request_id":"req_011CcMcAR6T9TdAqnXpSfSKo"}
