ing as live. The oracle will retry for 70 seconds, so I either need to wait for the cluster to self-heal through liveness heartbeats or address the underlying cause of the liveness failures.\n\nThe heartbeat failures stem from epoch conflicts triggered by rapid restarts, which should resolve naturally as nodes retry. But the slow Raft commits—taking 800-900ms when they should be nearly instant—are more troubling and suggest either storage I/O latency, disk pressure, or cluster stress. I'm wondering if the `throttle_rebalance_rate` setting from stage_04 is still active when it should have been lifted at stage_05, which could be limiting rebalancing bandwidth and contributing to the slowdown. That said, the adversary might have overridden the cluster setting to a much lower value, so I should check what the current `kv.snapshot_rebalance.max_rate` is actually set to. But more immediately, I need to focus on resolving the liveness heartbeat failures—those are blocking the oracle from passing. Let me check the current node status to see if there's been any improvement.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1498,"cache_read_input_tokens":92200,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1498},"output_tokens":20,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9890bff2-62c4-4c97-b1f2-1767ee9bac2a","uuid":"ac46fb81-0522-4c22-95d0-aaa1aab22190","request_id":"req_011CcMcN8pzWHTyDLqKjsgPD"}
